<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Phyllodoce</i> <i>empetriformis</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the dwarf shrub and herbaceous layers with <i>Allium</i> <i>validum</i>, <i>Antennaria</i> <i>media</i>, <i>Carex</i> <i>spectabilis</i>, <i>Castilleja</i> <i>miniata</i>, <i>Kalmia</i> <i>microphylla</i>, <i>Ligusticum</i> <i>grayi</i>, <i>Luetkea</i> <i>pectinata</i>, <i>Saxifraga</i> <i>aprica</i>, <i>Sibbaldia</i> <i>procumbens</i>, <i>Trisetum</i> <i>spicatum</i>, <i>Vaccinium</i> <i>cespitosum</i> and <i>Veratrum</i> <i>californicum</i>. </div>
</div>

		
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 1 m; canopy is intermittent to continuous. Herbaceous layer is intermittent to continuous and usually species rich. </div>
</div>

		
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Montane and subalpine wet meadows, slopes, and basins with late-lying snow and sub-irrigation from surrounding slopes. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Phyllodoce empetriformis</i> as a FACU* plant. </div>
</div>

		
