<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Phyllodoce empetriformis </i>is a dwarf, rhizomatous shrub to 50 cm tall. The evergreen leaves are shiny and needle-like. The red, urn-shaped flowers have included stamens and the fruits are capsules. The decumbent stems root when they contact the soil. <br/>
<br/>
The NVC (NatureServe 2007a) describes a <i>Phyllodoce empetriformis </i>dwarf-shrubland alliance in the Pacific Northwest. Stands of this heath are extensive in the Cascades and northern Rocky Mountains as part of the subalpine parkland mosaics at timberline (Franklin and Dyrness 1973). Observations suggest that the closely related <i>P. breweri </i>in the Sierra Nevada can grow in drier sites. </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Phyllodoce empetriformis</i> grows in California within the Klamath Mountains (M261A) and Southern Cascades (M261Df ) north of McGee Peak (Olmsted 1976). The description of heath meadows at Red Butte-Red Fir Ridge RNA on Mount Shasta (Imper 1988b) characterize stands in California. The species is more common in the Marble Mountains and Trinity Alps and appear sufficiently extensive to warrant alliance status; however, stands are unsampled. <i>Kalmia microphylla, Vaccinium cespitosum</i>, and other similar alliances appear to have substantial overlap in species composition; the relationships between these alliances need further evaluation. </div>
</div>

	

    
